revision.text:
'''Aposymbiosis''' occurs when [[symbiosis|symbiotic]] organisms live apart from one another (for example, a [[clownfish]] living independently of a [[sea anemone]]). Studies have shown that the lifecycles of both the [[Host (biology)|host]] and the symbiont are affected in some way, usually negative, and that for obligate symbiosis the effects can be drastic.<ref name="AEDouglas1992">A. E. Douglas, Requirement of pea aphids (''Acyrthosiphon pisum'') for their symbiotic bacteria, Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata (Historical Archive), Volume 65, Issue 2, Nov 1992, Pages 195–198</ref> Aposymbiosis is distinct from [[exsymbiosis]], which occurs when organisms are recently separated from a symbiotic association. Because symbionts can be vertically transmitted from parent to offspring or horizontally transmitted from the environment, the presence of an aposymbiotic state suggests that transmission of the symbiont is horizontal. A classical example of a symbiotic relationship with an aposymbiotic state is the Hawaiian bobtail squid ''[[Euprymna scolopes]]'' and the bioluminescent bacteria ''[[Vibrio fischeri]].'' While the nocturnal squid hunts, the bacteria emit light of similar intensity of the moon which camouflages the squid from predators. Juveniles are colonized within hours of hatching and ''Vibrio'' must outcompete other bacteria in the seawater through a system of recognition and infection. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Visick|first=Karen L.|last2=McFall-Ngai|first2=Margaret J.|date=2000-04-01|title=An Exclusive Contract: Specificity in the Vibrio fischeri-Euprymna scolopes Partnership|url=https://jb.asm.org/content/182/7/1779|journal=Journal of Bacteriology|language=en|volume=182|issue=7|pages=1779–1787|doi=10.1128/JB.182.7.1779-1787.2000|issn=0021-9193|pmid=10714980}}</ref> [[File:Hawaiian_Bobtail_Squid.jpg|alt=|border|right|286x286px|The Hawaiian bobtail squid uses its bacterial symbionts to evade predators.]]
== Use in research == Aposymbiotic organisms can be used as models to observe a variety of processes. Aposymbiotic ''Euprymna'' juveniles have been studied throughout colonization in order to determine the system of recognizing ''Vibrio fischeri'' in seawater. Coral polyps without their symbiont algae are models for coral calcification and the effects of the algae on coral pH regulation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ohno|first=Yoshikazu|last2=Iguchi|first2=Akira|last3=Shinzato|first3=Chuya|last4=Inoue|first4=Mayuri|last5=Suzuki|first5=Atsushi|last6=Sakai|first6=Kazuhiko|last7=Nakamura|first7=Takashi|date=2017-01-18|title=An aposymbiotic primary coral polyp counteracts acidification by active pH regulation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5241827/|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|doi=10.1038/srep40324|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5241827|pmid=28098180}}</ref>
