The '''Dual-Stage 4-Grid''' (DS4G) is an [[electrostatic ion thruster]] design developed by the [[European Space Agency]],<ref name=esaproject>{{cite web|title=Dual-Stage Gridded Ion Thruster (DS4G) | publisher = ESA Advanced Concepts Team — Advanced Propulstion | url = http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/projects/ds4g_overview.html}}</ref> in collaboration with the [[Australian National University]].<ref name=anuproject>{{cite web | title=Dual stage 4 grid thruster | publisher = ANU Centre for Plasmas &amp; Fluids | url = https://physics.anu.edu.au/cpf/sp3/ds4g/}}</ref> The design was derived by D. Fern from Controlled Thermonuclear Reactor experiments that use a 4-grid mechanism to accelerate ion beams.

A 4-grid ion thruster with only 0.2 m diameter is projected to absorb 250&nbsp;kW power. With that energy input rate, the thruster could produce a thrust of 2.5 [[Newton (unit)|N]]. The [[specific impulse]] (a measure of fuel efficiency), could reach 19,300 s at an exhaust velocity of 210&nbsp;km/s if [[xenon]] propellant were used.<ref name=esapaper>[http://www.esa.int/gsp/ACT/doc/PRO/ACT-RPR-PRO-IAC2006-DS4G-C4.4.7.pdf] THE INNOVATIVE DUAL-STAGE 4-GRID ION THRUSTER CONCEPT – THEORY AND EXPERIMENTAL RESULTS</ref> The potentially attainable power and thrust densities would substantially extend the power absorption of current ion thrusters to far more than 100&nbsp;kW. These characteristics facilitate the development of ion thrusters that can result in extraordinary high-end velocities.<ref name=esapaper />

Like with thruster concepts such as [[VASIMR]], the dual-stage-4-grid ion thrusters are mainly limited by the necessary power supply for their operation. For example, if solar panels were to supply more than 250&nbsp;kW, the size of the solar array would surpass the size of the solar panels of the [[International Space Station]]. To provide 250&nbsp;kW with [[Stirling radioisotope generator]]s would require roughly 1&nbsp;tonne of [[plutonium-238]] (for which the US stockpile as of 2013 was no more than 20&nbsp;kg<ref>{{cite web|last=Mosher|first=Dave|title=NASA’s Plutonium Problem Could End Deep-Space Exploration|url=https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2013/09/plutonium-238-problem/|publisher=Wired|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>), and so a nuclear thermal reactor would be needed.

